-- Italian Stocks: Ansaldo, Azimut, Fondiaria, Pirelli, Pop. Milano
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-12-09T16:50:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/eni-enel-intesa-sanpaolo-saipem-tenaris-italy-equity-market-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
increased for a third day, rising 139.61, or 0.7 percent, to
20,533.56 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Ansaldo STS SpA  (STS IM) lost 2.9 percent to 10.58 euros,
dropping for the first time in eight days. The shares of
Finmeccanica SpA’s (FNC IM) railway technology unit fell below
their 200-day moving average today.  Azimut Holding SpA  (AZM IM), Italy’s largest independent
fund manager, rose 3.9 percent to 6.55 euros as the Stoxx Europe
600 Index rose to its highest level since September 2008.  Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA  (BMPS IM) added 2.3
percent to 89.9 euro cents. Italian banks will perform better in
2011 than they did in 2010,  Giovanni Cagnoli , chief executive
officer for Italy at Bain & Co., told Il Sole 24 Ore in an
interview.  Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl  (PMI IM) increased 6.8
percent to 2.92 euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) and
 UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM), Italy’s biggest banks, advanced 2.3
percent to 2.21 euros and 2 percent to 1.73 euros, respectively.
 Unione di Banche Italiane SCPA  (UBI IM) increased 1.4 percent to
7.05 euros.  Fondiaria-Sai SpA  (FSA IM), Italy’s second-biggest insurer,
and its unit  Milano Assicurazioni SpA  (MI IM) climbed 5.5
percent to 6.30 euros and 4.6 percent to 1.20 euros,
respectively, as insurance stocks were the best performers in
Europe for a second day.  Premafin Finanziaria SpA  (PF IM),
Fondiaria-Sai’s main shareholder, surged 14 percent to 81.5 euro
cents.  Mediaset SpA  (MS IM) dropped for a third day this week,
falling 1.2 percent to 4.42 euros. Equita Sim SpA, which has a
“hold” rating on the broadcaster owned by Italian Prime
Minister  Silvio Berlusconi , said losing rights to televising
Champions League matches next season “would deteriorate its
pay-TV offer.”  Pirelli & C. SpA  (PC IM) lost 3 percent to 6.20 euros and
scooter maker  Piaggio & C. SpA  (PIA IM) slid 3.2 percent to 2.47
euros as automobile shares sank across Europe after a
representative of the China Automobile Industry Association said
that the world’s second-largest economy may end tax incentives
for buying passenger cars next year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 